<B>Originally posted by i3ullseye:</B><BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>The problem with Confusion, and most of our other spells, is that it TOTALLY removes a players control of themselves, and this sucks.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Not necessarily.  Somewhere on this board was a suggestion that confusion random switched the victim's target without updating him about it.  He could still try and help, but anytime he cast a spell or shot an arrow he might find it going somewhere he didn't want it to.  Even the best our confusion gets is 75% attacks ally.<P>Think about it: if you are using the level 13 or below, his attacks are still going to be hitting people in your realm, just not exactly who he wanted.  For the higher level confusions, he will either have to sit on his hands, risk hurting friends, or use spells such as healing that he doesn't mind working on random allies and that don't work on his enemies.<P>And of course he does get a chance to resist the spell!<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>Charm woudl be a one shot kill, period. And it woudl be a horrible tool for griefing.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>One shot kill with a 900 range, 4 second casting time that uses 25% of our power?  Oh, and it can be resisted (or you can fail to charm rather).  Sign me up!!!  No wait, I'll just make an archer instead, and get three times the range, more reliable one shot kill, better armor, some melee ability and stealth.<P>I really don't see the problem, especially since the method I listed isn't even a one shot kill!  He doesn't have to /release if he doesn't want to.  The only time charm would effectively be a one shot kill would be if you caught someone pretty much alone.  Root or mez followed by charm and he's gone.  Then again, in the current environment, you'd be killing him anyways.<P>-Zanthis
