<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
*scratches his chin*<P>Well, not necessarily |3ullseye.  Consider this: people in RvR have to understand that there's risks to what they're doing.  When they die and lie in the battlefield, everyone loses "control".  At that point, they're given a choice: wait for the save from a colleague, or release.<P>However, in raising a dead Enemy for our own pet, they would still be given the same choice: release now, or wait for a "save".  What kind of Save?  Well, as was stated, if the Sorcerer dies, then the person regains control of their bodies.  Perhaps healer classes could also be given some sort of counterspell themselves?<P>Mmm, but then if the Healer can always just easily counter the effects (maybe it'd end up cheaper than rezzing, since the Sorcerer did all the work, and they just countered the controlling effects), it would be a weak effort.  Unless the counterspell returns the player to the death state instead of releasing them in the live state (killing the Sorcerer alone would leave them alive when the spell is broken).<P>Each Sorcerer being able to have one lacky like that would be good.  However, if that is not good enough, (probably not) the spell could be empowered even more.  It might be treated similarly to Theurgist pets, in that the Sorcerer doesn't have direct control of them, and they instead maybe act like an Mob animal that attacks anti-realm members randomly with no guidance or direction.  Or if that is too overpowered, just have them maybe be random mobs that attack any players around them aggressively.  Maybe a confuse effect installed so that they send out hits to all around them.  Then a single Sorcerer could also raise multiple enemies before having to rest for power, then do it some more.  Heh, then you'd really see Archers targetting the people in robes.<P>Anyways, enough on that.  Bottom line is that charming like that is *not* removing control from the other player.  Death itself is a form of removing control: a charmed state is no different than death in that there is a choice, and maybe more negative effects for not releasing.  More of a gamble.<P>Allowing us to only "charm" dead players keeps it from being overpowered.  If we could charm live players, then it just might seem like a one-hit kill to them.  But charming dead people is different: they're already dead, they're still sitting there waiting for a rez.  Changing the after-death tactics too (instead of deciding whether to release or wait for rez, a player would have to gamble: is it better to release now, or wait for the death of the Sorcerer which could happen either soon or later?) would give Sorcerers a definate "place" in the battlefield.<P>The "Masters of Crowd Control" title might quickly change to "Masters of the Tide of Battle" influence, as once Sorcerer could change an iffy battle into a victory-certain one.<P>Sigma<BR>29 Sorcerer<BR>Percival
</FONT>
