In response to my question:<BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>Can anyone think of a way to force an xp death on a player given that rule?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE><B>i3ullseye wrote:</B><BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>yup, sure can.  What if i charm a Kobold and run his ass back to the gates of camelot? then he is pretty screwed huh?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>Uh, first, and maybe I'm just being all nutty here, but I'd <I>assume</I> that they'd prohibit you from bringing "enemy" pets into your own realm.  Many ways of handling this, including just having the "pet" fall over dead once he gets near to leaving your frontier.  That really should have gone without saying.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>Right now there is talk of stopping chat or vision while lying dead for just this reason. How out of character, unfair, and abusive is it to sit there and report to your friends behind enemy lines?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>It is generally a good idea to avoid making a necessary and regular part of a game too boring.  Preventing chatting while dead (which happens often) or while charmed, which could last awhile, would keep both of those events from being too boring.<P>Further, if you don't block sight then you aren't preventing people who have alternate means of communication from doing what everyone can do now.  In short, it won't "solve" the "problem."<P>Also, being able to see while dead is an important part of deciding to release or not.  Removing that will make it a toss up whether releasing is worth it and will actually remove some of the strategy behind RvR.  Also, keep in mind alternate communication will then be giving an even greater advantage.  Consider the guy on the phone with a group mate, "Don't release.  I see you and we'll rez you in a second."<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>Further, why in the hell does everyone automatically have telepathy anyway?<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>This one has been debated endlessly since text muds first existed and I'm not going to bring all that up except to say: Because it is more fun for more people that way.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>IF a charm ever happened, you would HAVE to lose your chat ability or it would be a horrible joke, and open to even MORE exploitation.<P>So you can't speak or understand the enemies language. but what if you had a buddy in the enemy realm, and he purposely charms you? thats right, now he can run around enemy posistions safe and sound, reporting all he sees back to his realm free of ANY repurcussions.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>And your own team would probably say, "Please kind Sorcerer, please do not bring a pet capable of spying into our positions."  Except there would be more cursing and it would be less polite.<P>You <B>cannot</B> prevent people from crossteaming, period.  They don't need charm to do it.  Further, unlike other methods of crossteaming, this one is visible.<P>And lastly, this also allows you to deliberately give false information to your pet.  Imagine letting him see your army moving out.  A few trees and some hills and he thinks the army is going somewhere so he tells his friends.  However, your army is actually moving elsewhere while you lead your pet off to draw the defends away.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>But it is one of the least resisted spells i cast from day to day usage. Further, i am not so sure it is EVER truly resisted, but simply fails. maybe it bypasses resist code, and PCs are not coded to handle spells of this nature properly anyway.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>First, just because it works one way in PvE doesn't mean it needs to work the same way in RvR.  The resists (or failures) can be coded to have whatever success rate suits play balance.  Also, it is obvious that this whole idea would require coding on Mythics part (altough not a terrible amount) and so just because the code might not currently support charm on players doesn't mean that is a reason not to do it.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">quote:</font><HR>See, regardless of what some may think, we analysed and hashed out a LOT of this in BETA. many items now reside in what is called the dead horse stables, where dead horse topics go to draw flies. when a Dev, or a TL, or any of the older BETA testers seems to dismiss something offhand, don't assume they are being flippiant. there is quite a bit of factual and experienced information supporting these decisions.<HR></BLOCKQUOTE>I've always found people tend to get too eager to put things in "dead horse bins."  Not saying that is the case here, just mentioning that has been my experience.  Further, "dead horse bins" tend to become, "we are tired of talking about it and don't want to do it just because we don't bins" without careful watching.<P>The best use I've ever found for the handling of really well hashed out issues that you decide not to implement is to periodicaly review them, especially with new people looking at them.  Otherwise you miss implementing something you should have just because everyone involved had cast the issue from their minds permanently.<P>What I am basically saying is: 1) it is technically doable, 2) it would make Sorcerers more useful in RvR (and they aren't currently dominating RvR), and 3) the complaints would be minimal (certainly far less than archers and stun/mez by a long shot).<P>-Zanthis
</FONT>
